35
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:43,200
**Lee Se-guk:** So I was working as a head chef in the Czech Republic. I needed a Korean chef, so I posted a recruitment ad on the internet.

36
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:43,600
**Host:** You were the head chef and recruited chefs.

37
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:53,400
**Lee Se-guk:** Yes. That chef put resumes in two places, one was a cruise ship and the other was the Korean restaurant where I was working.

38
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:56,800
**Host:** You recruited him and you left?

39
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:16,000
**Lee Se-guk:** Oh, that’s right. I hadn’t thought about it until then, but through this friend, my long-forgotten dream came back. “Oh, right, I wanted to work on a cruise.” “I’ll pass everything on to you, so you take over here. I’m going my way.”

40
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:17,400
**Host:** So, Costa? Italian too, right?

41
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:22,000
**Lee Se-guk:** Yes, this is also an Italian cruise line.

42
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:24,600
**Host:** But did Costa Cruises originally recruit Korean chefs?

43
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:29,400
**Lee Se-guk:** Korean chefs are more valuable than you think abroad.

44
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:32,000
**Host:** Really?

45
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:51,400
**Lee Se-guk:** A chef who can cook Korean food but can also make other countries' dishes with high quality. Ah, a Korean chef is someone who not only knows how to cook Korean food but also knows how to make other countries' food with high quality, at least from my perspective.

46
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:53,000
**Host:** Is it different from a Chinese or Japanese chef?

47
00:05:51,000 --> 00:06:02,600
**Lee Se-guk:** The difference between a Chinese chef making Korean food and a Korean chef making Chinese food is huge. Ah, Korean chefs do Chinese and Japanese food, too.

48
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:19,200
**Lee Se-guk:** For foreigners, it’s a bit difficult to do Korean food. So basically, the way they see Korean chefs abroad is someone who can speak English, who is good at Korean food, and who can also do international food to some extent.

49
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:19,400
**Host:** So they are highly utilized.

50
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:28,200
**Lee Se-guk:** They recruited someone saying they could do Korean food, and they were making it in a way that didn't make sense.

51
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:31,000
**Host:** When you travel abroad, there are Korean restaurants run by Chinese people occasionally. If you go and eat there...

52
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:32,800
**Other Speaker:** What are these guys doing?

53
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:36,400
**Lee Se-guk:** And cruise ships tend not to use Japanese chefs.

54
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:41,400
**Host:** Ah, because they only know how to do Japanese food.

55
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:45,800
**Lee Se-guk:** Yes, they are only good at Japanese food. But Korean chefs are good at everything.

56
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:52,400
**Host:** Now, CEO Lee. CEO Lee, how did you get into this? This isn't a market that's active in our country.

57
00:06:53,000 --> 00:07:02,600
**Lee Yong-ho:** That’s right. I’m a bit different from the three of them. I worked as a guide in Rome for about eight years.

58
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:00,400
**Host:** You started as a guide.

59
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:06,600
**Lee Yong-ho:** Yes, so around 2004, I went to Livorno, Italy, as a guide.

60
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:14,600
**Host:** You were working as a guide in Italy and then led a cruise trip? Were those people Korean?

61
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:19,000
**Lee Yong-ho:** Yes, that’s right. So they came to Italy to take an Italian cruise.

62
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:25,000
**Host:** Ah, so that’s what a cruise is like. That was your first experience too.

63
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:28,200
**Lee Yong-ho:** Yes, I only did tours for the guests who got off.

64
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:30,400
**Host:** And then you thought, “I want to ride it too.”

65
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:44,800
**Lee Yong-ho:** Yes, I wanted to ride it, and I thought, “That’s where the money is.” So I ended up running a cruise travel agency. In the beginning, there were no cruises starting from our country and going around the world, right?

66
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:56,400
**Lee Yong-ho:** Yes, it’s the same now. You have to take a plane to the first port of departure. And then you board there. Since I was in Italy, about 80% of Mediterranean routes are there.

67
00:07:53,000 --> 00:08:04,600
**Host:** You saw the potential for business. Usually, you see guests who fly in or come by train and guide them locally. But this time, guests came by ship.

68
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:37,600
**Lee Yong-ho:** Yes, that’s right. And they tipped well too. When the guests got off at the port of Livorno, I would take them on a tour of Florence and Tuscany and then take them back to the port, and they would board the ship. I would just wave goodbye from below, and the escorts would board the ship and give a simple briefing. “Today, we’ll meet at the ice rink at what time.”

69
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:42,000


70
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:51,600
**Host:** So CEO Lee only escorted them on land and when they moved to the ship, the escort on the ship explained everything. “I want to do that too.”

71
00:08:49,000 --> 00:09:02,600
**Lee Yong-ho:** Right. I was like, “Wait, there’s an ice rink on a ship?” So that was the first time I learned about it, which is a bit different from the three of them.

72
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:05,600
**Host:** That sounds similar. So how many times a year do you go on a ship as an escort?

73
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:09,600
**Lee Yong-ho:** As of 2019, for Mediterranean cruises, I went about once a month.

74
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:18,000
**Host:** Now, instead of ending on land, you go into the ship with the guests.

75
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:22,800
**Lee Yong-ho:** Yes, that’s right. I’m with them from Incheon Airport until we return to Incheon Airport.

76
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:32,600
**Host:** I’m jealous. Okay, so these are the people we’re talking to. If you board a ship, don’t you stay for a few months?

77
00:09:33,000 --> 00:10:00,200
**Gi Da-yong:** Crew members stay for six months and rest for two months. Once you start working, it’s for six months. We don’t just stay on one route. For example, the Alaska season is from June to September. Then you’re in the Alaska season for June, July, August, and September, and then for the remaining two months, you move toward Canada or New York, then the route changes.

78
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:56,000
**Host:** Do you change ships?

79
00:09:55,000 --> 00:10:04,600
**Gi Da-yong:** Yes, the route changes. Canada has the foliage season in September and October, and the Caribbean has it in January and February.

80
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:14,400
**Host:** Ship foliage tour? Lobster too. Is there such a thing as getting off work? Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, and then resting on the weekend?

81
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:18,000
**Lee Se-guk:** It’s Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Friday, Friday.

82
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:20,800
**Host:** You don’t have a day off.

83
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:24,400
**Lee Se-guk:** That’s why we rest for two months at once.

84
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:28,200
**Host:** You take it all at once. Is it the same for Europe?

85
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:39,600
**Cho Seon-ju:** I usually worked for eight to ten months. As you said, we work seven days a week. It’s quite intense. My department was Guest Services, like the front desk in a hotel.

86
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:51,600
**Lee Se-guk:** And I worked in the back office.

87
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:52,800
**Host:** What does the back office do?

88
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:56,800
**Lee Se-guk:** You can think of it as working in an office.

89
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:56,400
**Host:** Is the chef the same?

90
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:08,400
**Lee Se-guk:** I usually worked for eight to ten months. As far as I know, the maximum under international law is ten months. They can’t make you work longer than that.

91
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:14,400
**Host:** So you’re basically trapped on the ship once you board.

92
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:28,000
**Gi Da-yong:** Yes, that’s right. For Princess Cruises, when we say 140,000 to 160,000 tons, there are 3,000 passengers and 2,000 crew members, a total of 5,000 people. Many people call it a floating hotel.

93
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:49,600
**Host:** The reason I asked this question is that you work for six months straight. Then the system has to run like a city. Is there a police officer?

94
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:53,000
**Other Speaker:** Yes, there is.

95
00:11:53,000 --> 00:11:55,000
**Host:** A doctor?

96
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:56,000
**Other Speaker:** Yes, there is.

97
00:11:55,000 --> 00:12:02,200
**Host:** So you’re saying all the personnel needed for a city to function are there. It’s one world.

98
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:13,000
**Gi Da-yong:** Yes, it feels like Alice in Wonderland. When you go in there, the Wi-Fi is cut off too.

99
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:14,000
**Host:** It’s cut off?

100
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:24,000
**Gi Da-yong:** Yes, so we have to pay for it. It feels like you’ve come to another world. We communicate with each other using walkie-talkies.

101
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:24,200
**Host:** Then, for example, cell phones don’t work?

102
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:44,800
**Lee Se-guk:** It’s called Ship Wi-Fi, so you can use it if you pay. It’s expensive, that’s the problem. It’s not that it doesn’t work. So when we arrive at a port of call, everyone is just looking at their phones. Since it’s expensive, they can’t contact their families on the ship.

103
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:55,000
**Host:** So it’s like a city with its own rules. Its own schedule. So who is the mayor? The Captain?

104
00:12:57,000 --> 00:12:59,000
**Other Speaker:** Yes, the Captain.

105
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:00,000
**Host:** Is the Captain absolute?

106
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:02,000
**Other Speaker:** Absolute. Truly absolute.

107
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:06,200
**Host:** Does the Captain decide all the rules?

108
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:16,400
**Gi Da-yong:** All the rules. For example, if the weather gets bad, whether to continue on this route or not, he makes all those small decisions.

109
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:25,400
**Host:** Even if it’s a city they were originally supposed to go to, if the Captain says no, it can change.

110
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:35,000
**Gi Da-yong:** It changes. It’s not just the Captain’s whim, it’s because of the weather conditions. But the Captain makes the decision. He’s a capable Captain. The weather doesn’t have a mind of its own.

111
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:41,800
**Host:** CEO Lee. You said you were fascinated because there was an ice rink. What else is in there? You’ve been on the most ships, haven’t you?

112
00:13:46,000 --> 00:14:35,200
**Lee Yong-ho:** Yes, I’ve been on about 100 times. Other people only been on the ships they worked on, but I’ve been on many different ships. There’s an ice rink, and you can think of it as the 63 Building lying down. There are bumper cars, a water park, and a pool where you can surf. Indoor surfing too. An artificial pool, where you can ride waves. I’ve seen an artificial rock climbing wall. You can also do Ifly. It’s like wind blowing from below and you fly up. There’s a lot. They even take you on a helicopter from the ship. You take a helicopter and look at the ship you were on, going around the scenery. I haven’t tried it yet.

113
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:42,000


114
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:43,200
**Host:** There must be a theater, of course.

115
00:14:43,000 --> 00:15:12,200
**Lee Yong-ho:** Large theaters, small theaters, they are diverse for each concept. There are various restaurants like Western food, Oriental food, fusion food, and even a carousel. There’s everything. There’s even a zipline. It’s really just there. Everything in an amusement park or a hotel is there. When it’s 180,000 to 200,000 tons, it’s over 300 meters long and nearly 30 meters wide. So it’s much bigger than the 63 Building lying down.

116
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:17,000
**Other Speaker:** There’s even a sauna. Korean guests love it. And there’s also an acupuncturist.

117
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:26,000
**Host:** So it’s a city. A city that runs on its own logic and system.

118
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:37,800
**Other Speaker:** And almost all of that is free. Basically, it’s free to enjoy. If it’s something people particularly like or if it costs a lot to operate, then there’s a fee.

119
00:15:43,000 --> 00:16:21,800
**Host:** What about the food? In the early 90s, I went on a backpacking trip to Northern Europe and there was something called the Silja Line from Sweden to Finland. The Eurail Pass applied, so you could ride it for free. But the buffet was free. Word got out among early Korean backpackers. So these hungry Korean backpackers packed food in their bags when they got off. So after a few months, they stopped accepting Korean guests. The memory of a big ship in my head is that food is free. I’m curious. How about the food?

120
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:59,000
**Lee Se-guk:** If Korean guests packed food and got off, it would be a disaster on the ship. We calculated how much food would be used for how many days and loaded it, but they took it all. We prepared food thinking this many people would eat this much, but the food kept running out, so we kept refilling it. So there was a gap.

121
00:16:55,000 --> 00:17:00,200
**Host:** So is the food free? Or is some free and some paid?

122
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:20,600
**Gi Da-yong:** That’s a good question. There’s paid and free. One thing you must do is try as much food as possible on the cruise. Since there’s everything, I tell people to enjoy it all before they get off. But there are also paid ones. There are people who look for fine dining restaurants.

123
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:26,600
**Host:** Fine dining is paid. Then how is the basic free food provided? Buffet?

124
00:17:27,000 --> 00:18:05,800
**Gi Da-yong:** Yes. And there’s a formal restaurant. Korean guests don’t know this well, but you can keep ordering and eating. Some people like eating at the buffet, and the formal restaurant where you sit at a table and order from a menu is also operated. You can think of it as a course meal. Simply put, you can eat all day. From 6 AM to 10 AM, the buffet serves breakfast, and from 12 PM to 3 PM, it serves lunch, and from 6 PM to 9 PM, it serves dinner. The buffet is always open.

125
00:17:49,000 --> 00:17:51,400
**Host:** The buffet is always free.

126
00:17:51,000 --> 00:18:12,200
**Lee Yong-ho:** You can go whenever you want, and then you have a designated table in the formal restaurant. There, you order and eat a more properly prepared meal. You have your own seat. You can order everything from that seat, and they say you can eat up to seven meals a day.

127
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:13,400
**Host:** For free. That’s also free.

128
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:15,000
**Lee Yong-ho:** Yes.

129
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:25,000
**Host:** But there are so many foods provided in so many ways. You might not know what food is provided when. How do you know?

130
00:18:25,000 --> 00:18:29,000
**Gi Da-yong:** You have to look at the ship’s newspaper.

131
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:30,200
**Host:** A newspaper? It really is a city.

132
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:32,600
**Gi Da-yong:** Is a newspaper published on the ship?

133
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:33,000
**Gi Da-yong:** Yes.

134
00:18:32,000 --> 00:18:36,400
**Host:** Is the newspaper delivered to your room in the morning?

135
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:39,800
**Gi Da-yong:** Yes. It comes in the night before. Today’s ship news.

136
00:18:40,000 --> 00:18:43,200
**Host:** Is there a word from the Captain?

137
00:18:42,000 --> 00:19:23,600
**Gi Da-yong:** Yes, it’s all there. A word from the Captain, what the weather is like. From the dress code to the programs on the ship, everything is specified by the minute. So you look at the newspaper and plan your schedule from morning to night. Someone might go to the buffet at that time, someone else to the formal restaurant. As you wish. At what time, there’s a barbecue party at the outdoor pool. And at what time, what kind of dessert comes out for tea time. For a Hawaii cruise, Hawaiian food comes out. For an Alaska cruise, Alaskan food comes out.

138
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:32,600
**Host:** Author Gi, you have a lot to say. Once you start, it’s just flowing out. Some people might just follow those around and eat from morning to night.

139
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:37,000
**Lee Se-guk:** There are many.

140
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:38,000
**Gi Da-yong:** I did too.

141
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:50,600
**Lee Yong-ho:** The quality of the food is very high. Hotel level. And as mentioned, the traditional food of each port of call, or food with local sauces added, all those programs are integrated.

142
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:04,200
**Host:** I want to go on a cruise.

143
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:12,800
**Lee Yong-ho:** You like traveling, so eating new food every day for a week and then getting off with a stomach ache.

144
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:14,200
**Lee Yong-ho:** You get off with weight gained.

145
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:23,800
**Gi Da-yong:** That’s right. Guests really gain weight. That’s why there’s a gym on the cruise. You can run on a treadmill while looking at the sea.

146
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:24,200
**Host:** Then what kind of foods are paid?

147
00:20:25,000 --> 00:20:41,400
**Lee Se-guk:** The purpose of creating paid restaurants is to provide another experience. Rather than trying to sell more expensive things at a higher price, it’s for when you want to feel special today. A new experience. You can also propose.

148
00:20:41,000 --> 00:21:03,000
**Lee Se-guk:** That’s right. If it’s a wedding anniversary, instead of having the same meal, it’s for that kind of experience. I cooked barbecue at the outdoor pool, and then I went to the paid restaurant and made the same thing. You’re paying for a special atmosphere, not necessarily for a different quality of food.

149
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:27,000
**Other Speaker:** The quality is definitely different. Making for 1,000 people at once versus making one plate is different. It must be. They even promote Michelin chefs. They also promote paid restaurants like that. But the cost is only about $20 to $40 extra per person. It’s not that expensive. Cruises are not that expensive.

150
00:21:35,000 --> 00:21:38,200
**Host:** It’s not as expensive as people think.

